ish of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":9,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Anne Sayre Of Kent was born in 1373, in Deal, Kent, England. She married Adam Sayre. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1401, in Houghton, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 28, and was buried in Houghton, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1373–1401":"1373–1401","1346–1431":"1346–1431","1395–1477":"1395–1477","1401":"1401","1346":"1346","1477":"1477","1431":"1431","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","Dea